Riccati–Bessel functions: "S""n", "C""n", ξ"n", ζ"n".
Riccati–Bessel functions only slightly differ from spherical Bessel functions:
They satisfy the differential equation:
For example, this kind of differential equation appears in Quantum Mechanics while solving the radial component of the Schrödinger's Equation with hypothetical cylindrical infinite potential barrier. For reference see p. 154, Introduction to Quantum Mechanics by Griffiths, 2nd Edition. This differential equation, and the Riccati–Bessel solutions, also arises in the problem of scattering of electromagnetic waves by a sphere, known as Mie scattering after the first published solution by Mie (1908). See e.g., Du (2004) for recent developments and references.
Following Debye (1909), the notation formula_63 is sometimes used instead of formula_64.
